Here's a recommended structure:

**1. Make HTTP calls injectable**

```csharp
// In your MCP server project
public class WeatherTool
{
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;

    public WeatherTool(HttpClient httpClient)
    {
        _httpClient = httpClient;
    }

    public async Task<string> GetForecastAsync(string city)
    {
        var response = await _httpClient.GetAsync($"https://api.example.com/weather?city={city}");
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
    }
}
```

**2. Create the test project**

```bash
dotnet new xunit -n MyMcpServer.Tests
cd MyMcpServer.Tests
dotnet add reference ../MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj
dotnet add package Moq            # optional, for other interfaces
```

**3. Use a fake `HttpMessageHandler` to mock HTTP calls**

```csharp
public class FakeHandler : DelegatingHandler
{
    private readonly Func<HttpRequestMessage, HttpResponseMessage> _responder;

    public FakeHandler(Func<HttpRequestMessage, HttpResponseMessage> responder)
    {
        _responder = responder;
    }

    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        return Task.FromResult(_responder(request));
    }
}
```

**4. Write tests against the tool**

```csharp
public class WeatherToolTests
{
    [Fact]
    public async Task GetForecast_ReturnsExpectedJson()
    {
        // Arrange — fake the external API response
        var handler = new FakeHandler(req =>
        {
            Assert.Contains("city=Seattle", req.RequestUri!.Query);
            return new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.OK)
            {
                Content = new StringContent("{\"temp\":72}", Encoding.UTF8, "application/json")
            };
        });

        var httpClient = new HttpClient(handler);
        var tool = new WeatherTool(httpClient);

        // Act
        var result = await tool.GetForecastAsync("Seattle");

        // Assert
        Assert.Contains("72", result);
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task GetForecast_HandlesApiError()
    {
        var handler = new FakeHandler(_ =>
            new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError));

        var tool = new WeatherTool(new HttpClient(handler));

        await Assert.ThrowsAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            () => tool.GetForecastAsync("Seattle"));
    }
}
```

**Key principles:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| Inject `HttpClient` | Lets you swap in a fake handler at test time |
| `DelegatingHandler` | The standard .NET seam for faking HTTP — no third-party mocking library needed |
| Assert on the request | Verify your tool sends the right URL/headers/body |
| Return canned responses | Test happy path, errors, timeouts, malformed JSON, etc. |

This keeps your tool logic fully testable without any real network calls.
